      <text>
        The travel request forms take three hours: traveler information—name, species, origin, current status, medical clearances; route selection—preferred path, territorial sequence, estimated timeline; guide request specifications—terrain expertise needed, communication compatibility, coordination preferences; resource requirements—nutrition, shelter, water, medical support; emergency protocols—injury procedures, communication breakdowns, territorial disputes.

        It goes on and on.

        But I fill them out with energy I haven't felt in days—these forms have purpose and mean progress.

        Scout stays close throughout—bouncing approvingly whenever I complete a section; Buddy provides medical documentation from my records; Holloway coordinates everything with meticulous care.

        Holloway says, "Submit when ready."

        I hit submit.

        Holloway announces, "*Travel request filed!* Transmitting to territorial coordination networks now. Response timeline for guide assignment and approval typically twenty-four to forty-eight hours."

        Two days maximum I can handle two more days, especially knowing they lead somewhere.

        ¶

        Approval comes eighteen hours later.

        I'm eating breakfast mushroom paste, naturally when Holloway's fruiting bodies sprout with unusual enthusiasm.

        Holloway exclaims, "*Excellent news! Your travel request has been approved!* Guide assignments confirmed, territorial permissions secured, resource coordination established!"

        Scout bounces so enthusiastically they nearly roll off the table.

        I set down my spoon and ask, "Already? That fast?"

        Holloway explains, "Your situation qualified for expedited processing exceptional circumstances, time-sensitive query, unique species requiring specialized support. The networks coordinated efficiently your guides will arrive this afternoon for introductions and preparation. Departure is scheduled for dawn tomorrow."

        Tomorrow.

        Less than twenty-four hours.

        The energy that's been building for days suddenly crystallizes into the realization oh, this is really happening.

        I take a breath and ask, "That's... wow. Okay. Who are the guides? What do I need to know?"

        Holloway lists, "Two guides will accompany you through Territory One to the first boundary Leafwhisper experienced in forest navigation, excellent communication skills, very patient with non-plant travelers and Rootwalker terrain specialist, strong physical presence, direct personality—both highly qualified."

        I ask, "And they're okay with... a human traveling companion? Weird nutrition requirements, different communication style, probably slower than plant speed?"

        Holloway replies, "They're excellent with species diversity both have experience with unusual travel situations. Though I should mention Leafwhisper can be quite chatty, while Rootwalker prefers minimal conversation—contrasting styles, but they work well together."

        Of course plant guides have distinct personalities—why would that surprise me anymore?
      </text>
