        Leafwhisper and Rootwalker arrive mid-afternoon.

        Leafwhisper is immediately obvious — a mobile cluster of broad leaves attached to a flexible stem, about four feet tall, moving with graceful rustling. The leaves shimmer in the bioluminescent light, shifting between green and silver.

        Leafwhisper rustles and says, "Hello! You must be Kira! I'm Leafwhisper, your Territory One guide! So excited to meet you — we don't get many human travelers, actually this is my first human — very interesting species — I've been reviewing your documentation and the nutritional requirements are fascinating — quite different from standard plant metabolism, obviously, but the guides in other territories are already preparing compatible compounds —"

        The voice comes from the leaves themselves, vibrating to produce sound — fast, enthusiastic, cascading words without much pause for breath. Or whatever plants do instead of breathing.

        Leafwhisper continues, "—and I understand you're heading to Elder Heartwood, which is such an important journey — Elder is absolutely wonderful though very slow to respond so patience will be important — but you seem quite patient based on your wellness documentation — excellent adaptation scores, really impressive, actually —"

        Rootwalker cuts in, slow and deliberate, "Let her respond."

        Rootwalker appears in the doorway — if "appears" is the right word for something that moves like concentrated earth. A thick root structure forms a vaguely humanoid shape, about six feet tall, soil and small stones integrated into its composition. Each step is methodical, purposeful.

        Leafwhisper's leaves rustle, sheepish. "Sorry! I get excited. Tendency to talk too much. People mention it frequently."

        Buddy says cheerfully, "We noticed."

        Rootwalker says simply, "I'm Rootwalker — Territory One terrain guide. You're the human."

        I say, "I'm the human." I'm getting used to being the weird one.

        Rootwalker studies me — though it's unclear how, since there are no visible eyes. "Can you walk three days straight with rest breaks? — Eat fungal compounds without digestive distress? — Follow instructions during territorial boundary crossings?"

        I say, "Yes."

        I say, "Been doing it for a week."

        I say, "I can follow instructions."

        Rootwalker says, "Good. We leave at dawn — pack light."

        I ask, "What exactly should I pack?"

        Rootwalker says, "Nothing. Territories provide what you need."

        Leafwhisper rustles, "Well, personal items if you want them — comfort objects, documentation, your AI companion obviously — Scout seems very attached to you based on observation so Scout will come too, I assume — but yes, basically Rootwalker's right: we provide shelter and nutrition and water, you just need to show up ready to walk!"

        Scout bounces enthusiastically — obviously coming.

        I say, "I'm ready." And mean it.

        ¶

        The afternoon passes in final preparations.

        Remedy arrives for one last wound check. The robot examines my leg carefully, mechanical hands gentle.
      </text>
      <stage-directions>
