        Remedy announces, "Perfectly healed — full tissue regeneration, no infection risk, excellent structural integrity. You won't decompose from this injury — very successful treatment outcome."

        I say, "Thanks, Remedy — for everything. The chemistry really worked."

        Remedy states, "Chemistry always works — that's why it's better than bureaucracy." The robot tilts its head. Remedy continues, "Though I suppose bureaucracy is getting you to Elder Heartwood — maybe both have uses. Still prefer chemistry."

        Holloway's fruiting bodies rustle nearby — mild objection, but fond.

        Remedy says, "You'll be fine on the journey — the guides know human requirements. I've transmitted all your medical data to relevant territories — if you start decomposing unexpectedly, they'll know how to help."

        I say, "That's… comforting? I think?"

        Remedy answers, "Very comforting — decomposition prevention is important — travel safely, Kira. Come back and tell me how the journey went — I'm curious about the other territories' chemistry." The robot's mechanical hands pat my arm gently.

        The warmth in that simple statement surprises me. Remedy cares. In their weird, decomposition-focused way, they genuinely care.

        I promise, "I will — thank you, Remedy, for keeping me alive."

        Remedy says, "That's what chemistry's for."

        ¶

        Evening arrives quietly.

        I sit in my quarters — soon to be former quarters — with Scout settled nearby. My few belongings are already packed: salvaged data pad, medical documentation, the clothes I'd been wearing since the crash, cleaned and repaired by helpful vines.

        That's it — everything I own in this world.

        Buddy asks softly, "Kira — are you experiencing pre-journey anxiety? Your biometric readings suggest elevated stress markers — though not concerning levels."

        I answer, "Not anxious — just… thinking."

        Buddy asks, "About?"

        I say, "A week ago I crashed here — bleeding, stranded, no plan. Now I'm about to travel through seven plant territories to consult an ancient tree about getting home." I shake my head. "My life has gotten really weird."

        Buddy replies, "Objectively, yes — but you've adapted remarkably. I'm proud of you."

        The simple statement hits harder than expected. My throat tightens.

        I say, "Thanks, Buddy."

        Scout rolls closer and leans against my leg — solid, warm presence, ready for whatever comes next.

        Tomorrow we'll leave — three weeks through unknown territories: meeting new plants, navigating new protocols, eating mushroom paste in seven different jurisdictions.

        And at the end — Elder Heartwood — maybe answers, maybe just more questions.

        But at least I'll be moving — trying — choosing my path instead of accepting circumstances.

        I look around my quarters one last time: the bioluminescent walls that seemed so alien a week ago, the moss bed that somehow became comfortable, the spring feature where I drank alien water and survived.

        I lived here. Healed here. Learned to navigate impossible bureaucracy here.

        But *I'm not staying.*
      </text>
